  "answer": "To derive the conditional expectation E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0) for the Tobit selection model, we start with the Tobit model equations: y_1 = \mathbf{x}_1\pmb{\beta}_1 + u_1 and y_2 = max(0, \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2). Since y_1 is observed only when y_2 > 0, we can write the conditional expectation as E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0) = E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0). Using the law of iterated expectations, we can rewrite this as E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}) = E(E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0)). Now, we can condition on the event \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0. Since y_2 is a Tobit variable, we know that y_2 = \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 when \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0. Therefore, we can write E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0) = E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0) = \mathbf{x}_1\pmb{\beta}_1 + E(u_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0). Now, we need to find E(u_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0). Since u_1 is a random variable that is independent of \mathbf{x}, we can write E(u_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0) = E(u_1). However, we know that y_2 = \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 when \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0, so we can write E(u_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0) = E(u_1 | \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0). Using the fact that u_1 is independent of \mathbf{x}, we can write E(u_1 | \mathbf{x}\pmb{\delta}_2 + v_2 > 0) = E(u_1). Therefore, we have E(y_1 | \mathbf{x}, y_2 > 0) = \mathbf{x}_1\pmb{\beta}_1 + E(u_1). This is the conditional expectation of y_1 given \mathbf{x} and y_2 > 0 for the Tobit selection model. Procedure 17.3 follows from this result. First, we estimate \pmb{\delta}_2 by Tobit using all observations. Then, for y_{i2} > 0, we compute residuals \hat{v}_{i2} = y_{i2} - \mathbf{x}_i\hat{\pmb{\delta}}_2. Finally, we regress y_{i1} on \mathbf{x}_{i1} and \hat{v}_{i2} using the selected sample. The t-statistic on \hat{v}_{i2} tests for selection bias."
